\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The name 
\f1\b destroying angel
\f0\b0  applies to several similar, closely related species of deadly all-white {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushroom"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mushrooms}} in the genus {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita}}.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Destroying_angel#cite_note-AmanitaGenus-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [1]}} They are {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_bisporigera"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita bisporigera}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_ocreata"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. ocreata}} in eastern and western North America, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_virosa"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. virosa}} in Europe.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Destroying_angel#cite_note-AmanitaGenus-1"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [1]}} Another very similar species, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_verna"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A. verna}} or 
\f1\b fool's mushroom
\f0\b0 , was first described in France.
