\f2\i \cf2 Amanita bisporigera
\f0\i0  is a deadly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mushroom_poisoning"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 poisonous}} species of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungus"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 fungus}} in the family {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanitaceae"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanitaceae}}. It is commonly known as the 
\f1\b eastern North American destroying angel
\f0\b0  or just as the 
\f1\b destroying angel
\f0\b0 , although the fungus shares this latter name with three other lethal white {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Amanita}} species, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_ocreata"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A.\'a0ocreata}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_verna"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A.\'a0verna}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_virosa"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 A.\'a0virosa}}. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basidiocarp"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 fruit bodies}} are found on the ground in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mixed_coniferous"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 mixed coniferous}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deciduous_forest"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 deciduous forests}} of eastern North America south to Mexico, but are rare in western North America; the fungus has also been found in pine plantations in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colombia"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Colombia}}. The mushroom has a smooth white {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pileus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cap}} that can reach up to 10\'a0cm (4\'a0in) across, and a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipe_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 stipe}}, up to 14\'a0cm (5.5\'a0in) long by 1.8\'a0cm (0.7\'a0in) thick, that has a delicate white skirt-like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annulus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 ring}} near the top. The bulbous stipe base is covered with a membranous sac-like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volva_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 volva}}. The white {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamella_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gills}} are free from attachment to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipe_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 stalk}} and crowded closely together. As the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Specific_name_(botany)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 species name}} suggests, 
\f2\i A.\'a0bisporigera
\f0\i0  typically bears two {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spore"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 spores}} on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basidia"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 basidia}}, although this characteristic is not as immutable as was once thought. \

\f2\i Amanita bisporigera
\f0\i0  was {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species_description"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 described}} as a new species in 1906. It is {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classification_(biology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 classified}} in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Section_(botany)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 section}} 
\f2\i Phalloideae
\f0\i0  of the genus 
\f2\i Amanita
\f0\i0  together with other {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amatoxin"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 amatoxin}}-containing species. Amatoxins are {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_peptide"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cyclic peptides}} which {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enzyme_inhibition"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 inhibit}} the enzyme {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RNA_polymerase_II"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 RNA polymerase II}} and interfere with various cellular functions. The first symptoms of poisoning appear 6 to 24 hours after consumption, followed by a period of apparent improvement, then by symptoms of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acute_liver_failure"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 liver}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acute_kidney_injury"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 kidney failure}}, and death after four days or more. 
\f2\i Amanita bisporigera
\f0\i0  closely resembles a few other white amanitas, including the equally deadly 
\f2\i A.\'a0virosa
\f0\i0  and 
\f2\i A.\'a0verna
\f0\i0 . These species, difficult to distinguish from 
\f2\i A.\'a0bisporigera
\f0\i0  based on visible field characteristics, do not have two-spored {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basidia"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 basidia}}, and do not stain yellow when a dilute solution of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potassium_hydroxide"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 potassium hydroxide}} is applied. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 DNA}} of 
\f2\i A.\'a0bisporigera
\f0\i0  has been partially {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA_sequencing"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 sequenced}}, and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 genes}} responsible for the production of amatoxins have been determined. \
